The above results indicate that the device can realize both stable dual-resistance resistive switching and stable three-resistance resistive switching. In addition, the transition between the two modes is reversible via the modulation of the Icc
                      (Fig. S10), which is rarely reported to the best of our knowledge (Table 1
                     ). This indicates that the GO/SF/GO memristor developed here can combine both binary storage and ternary storage, resulting in an improvement of the storage capacity of a potential device and the enrichment of the storage mode. Moreover, compared with multilevel memristors based on inorganic–organic composites, the memristive functional layer composed of SF (natural material) and GO (synthetic material) endows the device with good biocompatibility and environment-friendly nature [29–32], resulting in potential application in the construction of bio-friendly multilevel storage memristors.
